Recall that the general equation for a second degree Taylor polynomial
at \emph{a} is given by:

\begin{align*}
T_2(x)=f(a)+f'(a)(x-a)+\frac{f''(a)}{2}(x-a)^2
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
To find the second degree Taylor polynomial, we use the equation

\begin{align*}
T_2(x)=f(a)+f'(a)(x-a)+\frac{f''(a)}{2}(x-a)^2
\end{align*} We know that \emph{a}
=4 and that $f$(x)=$\sqrt{x}$. We can easily compute the derivatives to
get

\begin{align*}
f'(x)&=\frac{1}{2}x^{-1/2}\\
f''(x)&=-\frac{1}{4x^{3/2}}
\end{align*} Plugging this all in to the Taylor equation, we get:

\begin{align*}
T_2(x)&=f(a)+f'(a)(x-a)+\frac{f''(a)}{2}(x-a)^2\\
&=f(4)+f'(4)(x-4)+\frac{f''(4)}{2}(x-4)^2\\
&=\sqrt{4}+\frac{1}{2}4^{-1/2}(x-4)+\frac{-\frac{1}{4\times 4^{3/2}}}{2}(x-4)^2\\
&=2+\frac{1}{4}(x-4)-\frac{1}{64}(x-4)^2\\
&=2+\frac{x-4}{4}-\frac{(x-4)^2}{64}
\end{align*}

